
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    `dbus-daemon` yek barname ast ke mesle yek postchi baraye barname-ha dar Linux kar mikonad. Yani barname-ha mitoonan payam-ha ra be vasileye `dbus-daemon` baraye hamdigar beferestand. In komak mikonad ta barname-ha ba ham moratebtar va hamahangtar bashand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--session`  --> 👤 Ra'e andazi (start) yek instance az `dbus-daemon` baraye yek user (session).
    🔹 `--system`   --> ⚙️ Ra'e andazi yek instance az `dbus-daemon` baraye system (hameye user-ha).
    🔹 `--print-address[=NUMBER]`  --> ✉️ Chap (print) address instance az `dbus-daemon` dar stdout. Number (adad) moshakhas mikonad chand instance dar hal ra'e andazi ast.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dbus-daemon --session

    🔹 Ra'e andazi yek instance az `dbus-daemon` baraye session user jari (current user session).

    $ dbus-daemon --system

    🔹 Ra'e andazi yek instance az `dbus-daemon` baraye system.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dbus-daemon --session --print-address=1

    🔹 Ra'e andazi yek instance az `dbus-daemon` baraye session user va chap address instance dar terminal. In address baraye barname-ha zaruri ast ta ba `dbus-daemon` ertebat bargharar konand.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    `dbus-daemon` is a message bus system daemon. It acts like a postal service for applications in Linux, allowing them to send messages to each other. This helps applications to be more organized and coordinated.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--session`  --> 👤 Starts a `dbus-daemon` instance for a user session.
    🔹 `--system`   --> ⚙️ Starts a `dbus-daemon` instance for the entire system.
    🔹 `--print-address[=NUMBER]`  --> ✉️ Prints the address of the `dbus-daemon` instance to stdout. NUMBER specifies which instance to print the address for, in case multiple instances are running.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dbus-daemon --session

    🔹 Starts a `dbus-daemon` instance for the current user session.

    $ dbus-daemon --system

    🔹 Starts a `dbus-daemon` instance for the system.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dbus-daemon --session --print-address=1

    🔹 Starts a `dbus-daemon` instance for the user session and prints the instance's address to the terminal. This address is necessary for applications to communicate through the `dbus-daemon`.
